Raw dev notes -- Agents, Anonymization, and the DOCX Deep Dive

Man, what a week. This project, Weaverai_Agents_MCP, is basically my attempt to build a robust AI agent system that can handle complex, multi-step tasks. Think of it as a central brain (the MCP part) orchestrating different AI tools and services. The core idea is to combine Flowise for agent orchestration with n8n for workflow automation and skill integration. It's all about making these agents smarter and more capable of interacting with real-world data and processes.

This past week was a whirlwind. Kicked it off by getting the basic Flowise + n8n structure in place. Then, a huge chunk of work went into building out the n8n workflow vector database. This involved writing scripts to ingest existing n8n workflows, clean up their JSON, and then query them. I managed to expand the dataset to a whopping 6902 workflows – that was a grind, but essential for the agent to have a rich "skill library." Had a minor hiccup with Windows encoding early on, which is always fun. To make the search results actually useful, I integrated Voyage's rerank-2.5-lite, which made a noticeable difference in relevance. The "workflow build loop" was a big step, allowing the agent to dynamically construct n8n workflows based on a task.

Then came the big push: the WAIP (Weaverai Anonymizer Pipeline). This is a beast. It involved building out a full anonymization service, complete with n8n helpers, a LiteLLM skill for model integration, and even a DOCX translation service. Getting the DOCX translation to work, especially with the anonymizer, was a real challenge. I had to dive deep into DOCX structure to handle things like RTL/LTR bidirectional text, stripping it from styles, section properties, and even table visual properties. That was a rabbit hole I didn't expect to go down! Debugging the AI prompts for `supergemma` and the `translate-docx` workflow was also tricky – getting the AI to "think" correctly without overthinking every single request. I also added a `/deploy` endpoint for remote updates, which is super handy for continuous integration. Oh, and dealing with task runner timeouts – bumping the Code node deadline to 290s was a necessity.

Honestly, this week felt like drinking from a firehose. The sheer volume of features and integrations was intense. The biggest struggle was definitely the DOCX manipulation and getting the anonymizer to be robust across different document structures and languages. The bidi text issue was a real head-scratcher, requiring a deep dive into XML and document standards I hadn't touched in ages. It felt like I was constantly context-switching between vector databases, AI prompts, n8n workflows, and low-level document parsing.

But man, it's also incredibly satisfying to see it all come together. Building a system that can dynamically find, build, and execute complex workflows, and then handle something as intricate as document anonymization and translation, feels like a huge leap. It reinforces the idea that these AI agents aren't just chatbots; they can be powerful automation engines. I learned so much about the practicalities of integrating multiple AI services and the hidden complexities of seemingly simple tasks like "translate a document." It's a testament to how much you can achieve when you just keep pushing through the problems, one commit at a time.

Next up: Refine the anonymizer's accuracy and expand its capabilities to more document types.
